📋 Original Step Order (Before My Changes):
1. Unit test - Ran gradle test || true (with failure ignored)
2. Gradle Build - Ran gradle bootJar to build the JAR file
3. Docker Build - Built and pushed Docker image
4. Sonarqube scan - Ran gradle clean build sonarqube (this deleted previous coverage data!)
5. Deploy - Deployed the application


Original Order:


1. Unit test (gradle test || true)
2. Gradle Build (gradle bootJar)
3. Docker Build
4. Sonarqube scan (gradle clean build sonarqube) ❌ Problem: clean deleted coverage!
5. Deploy


New Order (After My Changes):
1. Unit test, Build and Sonarqube scan (gradle clean build jacocoTestReport sonarqube)
2. Docker Build
3. Deploy

✅ Why the New Order is Correct:
The new order is logically correct because:
1. Test → Build → Analyze happens in one step (no data loss)
2. Docker Build comes after the JAR is created (artifacts are passed)
3. Deploy happens last (after Docker image is pushed)
The original order had Sonarqube scan AFTER Docker Build, which was illogical because:
* Code quality analysis should happen before building the Docker image
* If SonarQube fails quality gates, you shouldn't deploy bad code
* The gradle clean in step 4 was deleting the coverage data from step 1
The new order is the correct CI/CD flow! ✅







